{"title_page": "Kanniyakumari railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name                = [[File:Indian_Railways_Suburban_Railway_Logo.svg|50px]]<br>Kanniyakumari\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| type                = [[Express train]] & [[Passenger train]] station\n| style               = Indian Railways\n| image               = GKN Kanniyakuari Railway DSC 1000.JPG\n| image_size          =\n| image_caption       = A platform of the station\n| address             = [[National Highway 7]], [[Kanniyakumari]], [[Tamil Nadu]],\n| line                = [[Thiruvananthapuram-Nagercoil-Kanyakumari railway line]]\n| other               = Taxi Stand, Auto Rickshaw stand\n| structure           = Standard (on ground station)\n| platform            = 4\n| depth               = \n| levels              =\n| tracks              = 6\n| opened              =\n| electrified         = Yes\n| grade               =\n| closed              =\n| rebuilt             =\n| ADA                 = {{Access icon|20px}}\n| code                = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = CAPE\n  | zone = [[Southern Railway zone]]\n  | division = [[Thiruvananthapuram railway division|Thiruvananthapuram]]\n  }}\n| owned               = [[Indian Railways]]\n| operator            = [[Southern Railway zone]]\n| status              = Functioning (doubling)\n| services            = \n| map_type            = India#India Tamil Nadu\n| map_dot_label       = Kanniyakumari\n| coordinates         = {{coord|8|5|16|N|77|32|48|E|display=inline}}\n| elevation           = {{convert|36|m|ft}}\n}}\n'''Kanniyakumari railway station''' (formerly known as '''Cape Comorin railway station''', station code: '''CAPE''') is a railway terminus of the [[Indian Railways]] serving the coastal city of [[Kanyakumari]] in the state of [[Tamil Nadu]].\n\n==Administration==\nIt is a part of the [[Thiruvananthapuram railway division]] of [[Southern Railway zone]]. It's the southernmost railway station in India. The Kanyakumari rail station is located in the heart of Kanniyakumari and is only {{convert|1|km}} away from Kanniyakumari beach.\n\n==Services==\nSeveral express trains connect Kanyakumari with the rest of India. Two of the longest trains operated by the Indian Railways \u2014 [[Dibrugarh\u2013Kanyakumari Vivek Express]] {{convert|4283|km}} and [[Himsagar Express]] {{convert|3789|km}} depart from here. It has daily trains to Chennai, Bangalore and Mumbai as well as direct trains for Rameswaram, New Delhi, Howrah,  Jammu, Dibrugarh, Thiruvananthapuram and other cities.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://indiarailinfo.com/departures/kanniyakumari-cape/1010#st | title=Departures from CAPE/Kanniyakumari| website=India Rail Info}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n{{Gallery\n|title=Kanniyakumari railway station\n|width=150 | height=160\n|align=center\n|footer=\n|File:Kanyakumari Tirunelveli Passenger.jpg\n |alt1=\n |Kanyakumari Tirunelveli Passenger in Platform 1\n|File:\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbe\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bbf.jpg\n |alt2=\n |View of the platforms from the [[buffer stop]] of the rail tracks.\n|File:Kanyakumari_Railway_Station.jpg\n |alt3=\n |Station's fa\u00e7ade\n|File:Kanyakumari Station Rail Deadend.jpg\n |alt4=\n |Kanyakumari Station rail dead-end\n}}\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IndiaRailInfo|1010}}\n{{Ccat|Kanyakumari railway station}}\n{{Railway stations in Tamil Nadu}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Kanyakumari district]]\n[[Category:Railway terminus in India]]\n[[Category:Thiruvananthapuram railway division]]\n[[Category:Transport in Kanyakumari]]\n\n{{TamilNadu-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{unreferenced|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name                = [[File:Indian_Railways_Suburban_Railway_Logo.svg|50px]]<br>Kanniyakumari\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| type                = [[Express train]] & [[Passenger train]] station\n| style               = Indian Railways\n| image               = GKN Kanniyakuari Railway DSC 1000.JPG\n| image_size          =\n| image_caption       = A platform of the station\n| address             = [[National Highway 7]], [[Kanniyakumari]], [[Tamil Nadu]],\n| line                = [[Thiruvananthapuram-Nagercoil-Kanyakumari railway line]]\n| other               = Taxi Stand, Auto Rickshaw stand\n| structure           = Standard (on ground station)\n| platform            = 4\n| depth               = \n| levels              =\n| tracks              = 6\n| opened              =\n| electrified         = Yes\n| grade               =\n| closed              =\n| rebuilt             =\n| ADA                 = {{Access icon|20px}}\n| code                = {{Indian railway code\n  | code = CAPE\n  | zone = [[Southern Railway zone]]\n  | division = [[Thiruvananthapuram railway division|Thiruvananthapuram]]\n  }}\n| owned               = [[Indian Railways]]\n| operator            = [[Southern Railway zone]]\n| status              = Functioning (doubling)\n| services            = \n| map_type            = India#India Tamil Nadu\n| map_dot_label       = Kanniyakumari\n| coordinates         = {{coord|8|5|16|N|77|32|48|E|display=inline}}\n| elevation           = {{convert|36|m|ft}}\n}}\n'''Kanniyakumari railway station''' (formerly known as '''Cape Comorin railway station''', station code: '''CAPE''') is a railway terminus of the [[Indian Railways]] serving the coastal city of [[Kanyakumari]] in the state of [[Tamil Nadu]].\n\n==Administration==\nIt is a part of the [[Thiruvananthapuram railway division]] of [[Southern Railway zone]]. It's the southernmost railway station in India. The Kanyakumari rail station is located in the heart of Kanniyakumari and is only {{convert|1|km}} away from Kanniyakumari beach.\n\n==Services==\nSeveral express trains connect Kanyakumari with the rest of India. Two of the longest trains operated by the Indian Railways \u2014 [[Dibrugarh\u2013Kanyakumari Vivek Express]] {{convert|4283|km}} and [[Himsagar Express]] {{convert|3789|km}} depart from here. It has daily trains to Chennai, Bangalore and Mumbai as well as direct trains for Rameswaram, New Delhi, Howrah,  Jammu, Dibrugarh, Thiruvananthapuram and other cities.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://indiarailinfo.com/departures/kanniyakumari-cape/1010#st | title=Departures from CAPE/Kanniyakumari| website=India Rail Info}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n{{Gallery\n|title=Kanniyakumari railway station\n|width=150 | height=160\n|align=center\n|footer=\n|File:Kanyakumari Tirunelveli Passenger.jpg\n |alt1=\n |Kanyakumari Tirunelveli Passenger in Platform 1\n|File:\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbe\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bbf.jpg\n |alt2=\n |View of the platforms from the [[buffer stop]] of the rail tracks.\n|File:Kanyakumari_Railway_Station.jpg\n |alt3=\n |Station's fa\u00e7ade\n|File:Kanyakumari Station Rail Deadend.jpg\n |alt4=\n |Kanyakumari Station rail dead-end\n}}\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IndiaRailInfo|1010}}\n{{Ccat|Kanyakumari railway station}}\n{{Railway stations in Tamil Nadu}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Kanyakumari district]]\n[[Category:Railway terminus in India]]\n[[Category:Thiruvananthapuram railway division]]\n[[Category:Transport in Kanyakumari]]\n\n{{TamilNadu-railstation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cerebellum", "label": "safe", "comment": "mistagged article - it has a source.you can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kanniyakumari_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Agalmaceros", "text_new": "{{short description|Extinct genus of deer}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n|fossil_range = [[Pleistocene]] ([[Uquian]]-[[Lujanian]])<br />~{{fossil range|2.588|0.012}}\n|taxon = Agalmaceros\n|authority = [[Robert Hoffstetter|Hoffstetter]] 1952\n|subdivision_ranks = [[Species]]\n|subdivision = ''A. blicki'' <small>[[Childs Frick|Frick]] 1937</small>\n|type_species = ''A. blicki''\n|type_species_authority = [[Childs Frick|Frick]] 1937\n|display_parents = 4\n}}\n\n'''''Agalmaceros''''' is an [[extinction|extinct]] [[genus]] of deer of the [[Deer|Cervidae]] family, that lived in [[South America]] during the [[Pleistocene]]. The [[type species]] is ''A. blicki''.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Agalmaceros blicki''|url=http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?a=taxonInfo&taxon_no=247647|website=Fossilworks.org|accessdate=8 August 2017}}</ref> Remains have only been found in [[Ecuador]]. It showed a clear affinity to [[Andes|Andean]] or temperate [[habitat]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ochsenius|first=Claudio|date=1985|title=Pleniglacial Desertization, Large-AnimalMassExtinction and Pleistocene-Holocene Boundary in South America|url=http://revistanortegrande.cl/archivos/12/04_12_1985.pdf|journal=Revista de Geograf\u00eda Norte Grande|volume=12|pages=35\u201347}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> ''Agalmaceros blicki'' is estimated to have been {{convert|60|kg|lb}} in weight.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lyons|first=Kathleen|date=2004|title=Of mice, mastodons and men: human-mediated extinctions on four continents|url=http://biology.unm.edu/fasmith/Web_Page_PDFs/Lyons_et_al_2004_EER.pdf|journal=Evolutionary Ecology Research|volume=6|pages=339\u2013358}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q43657080}}\n\n[[Category:Prehistoric cervoids]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene even-toed ungulates]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene extinctions]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of South America]]\n[[Category:Uquian]]\n[[Category:Ensenadan]]\n[[Category:Lujanian]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1952]]\n\n\n{{Paleo-eventoedungulate-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|An extinct genus of mammals belonging to the deer, muntjac, roe deer, reindeer, and moose family of ruminants}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n|fossil_range = [[Pleistocene]] ([[Uquian]]-[[Lujanian]])<br />~{{fossil range|2.588|0.012}}\n|taxon = Agalmaceros\n|authority = [[Robert Hoffstetter|Hoffstetter]] 1952\n|subdivision_ranks = [[Species]]\n|subdivision = ''A. blicki'' <small>[[Childs Frick|Frick]] 1937</small>\n|type_species = ''A. blicki''\n|type_species_authority = [[Childs Frick|Frick]] 1937\n|display_parents = 4\n}}\n\n'''''Agalmaceros''''' is an [[extinction|extinct]] [[genus]] of deer of the [[Deer|Cervidae]] family, that lived in [[South America]] during the [[Pleistocene]]. The [[type species]] is ''A. blicki''.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Agalmaceros blicki''|url=http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?a=taxonInfo&taxon_no=247647|website=Fossilworks.org|accessdate=8 August 2017}}</ref> Remains have only been found in [[Ecuador]]. It showed a clear affinity to [[Andes|Andean]] or temperate [[habitat]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ochsenius|first=Claudio|date=1985|title=Pleniglacial Desertization, Large-AnimalMassExtinction and Pleistocene-Holocene Boundary in South America|url=http://revistanortegrande.cl/archivos/12/04_12_1985.pdf|journal=Revista de Geograf\u00eda Norte Grande|volume=12|pages=35\u201347}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> ''Agalmaceros blicki'' is estimated to have been {{convert|60|kg|lb}} in weight.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lyons|first=Kathleen|date=2004|title=Of mice, mastodons and men: human-mediated extinctions on four continents|url=http://biology.unm.edu/fasmith/Web_Page_PDFs/Lyons_et_al_2004_EER.pdf|journal=Evolutionary Ecology Research|volume=6|pages=339\u2013358}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q43657080}}\n\n[[Category:Prehistoric cervoids]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene even-toed ungulates]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene extinctions]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of South America]]\n[[Category:Uquian]]\n[[Category:Ensenadan]]\n[[Category:Lujanian]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1952]]\n\n\n{{Paleo-eventoedungulate-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tridwoxi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changingshort descriptionfrom \"An extinct genus of mammals belonging to the deer, muntjac, roe deer, reindeer, and moose family of ruminants\" to \"Extinct genus of deer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agalmaceros"}
{"title_page": "Gene Lorendo", "text_new": "{{short description|American football and basketball coach}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Gene Lorendo\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1921|12|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Gilbert, Minnesota]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2001|4|15|1921|12|7}}\n| death_place = [[Alpharetta, Georgia]]\n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1947\u20131949\n| player_team2 = [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]]\n| player_sport3 = Basketball\n| player_years4 = 1942\u20131943\n| player_team4 = [[Oshkosh All-Stars]]\n| player_years5 = 1946\u20131949\n| player_team5 = [[Georgia Bulldogs basketball|Georgia]]\n| player_positions = [[End (gridiron football)|End]] (football)<br/>[[Forward (basketball)|Forward]] (basketball)\n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1950\n| coach_team2 = [[Presbyterian Blue Hose football|Presbyterian]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1951\u20131975\n| coach_team3 = [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] (assistant)\n| coach_sport4 = Basketball\n| coach_years5 = 1950\u20131951\n| coach_team5 = [[Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball|Presbyterian]]\n| overall_record = 17\u20139 (basketball)\n| championships = \n;Basketball:\n* [[South Carolina Little Four|SCLF]] regular season (1951)\n* SCLF Tournament (1951)\n| awards = \n}}\n'''Eugene Lionel Lorendo''' (December 7, 1921 \u2013 April 15, 2001) was an American college [[American football|football]] and [[basketball]] coach, as well as a professional basketball player for one season. He played in the [[National Basketball League (United States)|National Basketball League]] for the [[Oshkosh All-Stars]] in 1942\u201343, served as [[Presbyterian College]]'s head men's basketball coach in 1950\u201351, but is perhaps most remembered for his twenty-five seasons spent as an assistant football coach for [[Auburn University]] between 1951 and 1975.\n\n==Early life and playing careers==\nA native of [[Gilbert, Minnesota]], Lorendo attended Gilbert High School and [[varsity letter|lettered]] in football, basketball, and track.<ref name=book>{{cite web| last=Blankenship |first=Allison | title = 'Lorendo' follows untold story of former AU assistant coach | work =Auburn Villager| publisher =| date =November 19, 2015 | url =https://www.auburnvillager.com/news/lorendo-follows-untold-story-of-former-au-assistant-coach/article_b29db1a6-8ecd-11e5-bce3-eb3f8042d82c.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=pfarchives>{{cite web| title = Gene Lorendo | work =| publisher =Pro Football Archives| date = | url =https://www.profootballarchives.com/playerl/lore00030.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=peach>{{cite web| title = Gene Lorendo | work =Peach Basket Society| publisher =| date = January 6, 2015 | url =http://peachbasketsociety.blogspot.com/2016/01/gene-lorendo.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> At 6'3\" and 215 pounds,<ref name=viking>{{cite web| title = Viking of the Plains| work =Auburn Magazine| publisher =[[Auburn University]]| date =November 12, 2015 | url =https://issuu.com/alumniau/docs/auburn-magazine-winter-2015/20 | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> and of [[French-Canadian]] descent,<ref name=viking/> Lorendo was a large man who was later written about resembling a [[viking]].<ref name=viking/> Utilizing this stature helped him play football, basketball, and track when he attended college.<ref name=support>{{cite web|last = Ringer| first=Ken |title = Coach Gene Lorendo Biography | work =Support Auburn| publisher =| date = June 27, 2016 | url =http://www.supportauburn.com/products/gallery-6 | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome sources claim that Lorendo played football and basketball at Evelith Junior College ({{circa|1940}}), the [[University of Northern Iowa]] ({{circa|1942}}), ''and'' the [[University of Georgia]] (1946\u20131949).<ref name=peach/><ref name=support/><ref name=justsports>{{cite web| title = Gene Lorendo Statistics| work =Just Sports Stats| publisher =| date = | url =https://www.justsportsstats.com/basketballstatsindex.php?player_id=lorenge01 | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=pbe>{{cite web| title = Gene Lorendo | work =| publisher =Pro Basketball Encyclopedia| date = | url =https://probasketballencyclopedia.com/player/gene-lorendo/| accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> The only verifiable statistics and records, however, can trace him to his time at Georgia.\n\nBefore Lorendo attended Georgia, he played one season of professional basketball for the [[Oshkosh All-Stars]] in the [[National Basketball League (United States)|National Basketball League]] during 1942\u201343.<ref name=peach/><ref name=bbr>{{cite web| title = Eugene Lorendo NBL stats| work =basketball-reference.com| publisher =Sports Reference LLC| date = | url =https://www.basketball-reference.com/nbl/players/l/loreneu01n.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> A [[forward (basketball)|forward]], he averaged  1.9 points per game.<ref name=bbr/> Lorendo then served in the [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] in [[World War II]]; stops during his service included [[Pearl Harbor]], [[Iwo Jima]], and [[Okinawa]].<ref name=support/><ref name=book/>\n\nWhen Lorendo enrolled at the University of Georgia in fall 1946, he joined the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|football]], [[Georgia Bulldogs basketball|basketball]], and [[Georgia Bulldogs track and field|track]] teams.<ref name=support/><ref>{{cite web| title = All-Time Georgia Football Lettermen | work =GeorgiaDogs.com | publisher =University of Georgia| date =February 15, 2002 | url =https://georgiadogs.com/news/2002/2/15/All_Time_Georgia_Football_Lettermen.aspx | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> In football he played [[wide receiver]], where in 1949 he led the [[Southeastern Conference]] in receiving.<ref name=support/> He also appeared in three [[bowl game]]s: the [[1947 Sugar Bowl]], [[1948 Gator Bowl]], and [[1949 Orange Bowl]].<ref name=support/>\n\nIn spring 1950, he was chosen in the [[1950 NFL Draft]] by the [[Green Bay Packers]] (11th round, 134th overall) but never played a game in the league.<ref name=pfarchives/>\n\n==Coaching careers==\n===Football===\nOnce Lorendo's playing days were over, he accepted [[Presbyterian College]]'s offer to coach football and basketball, starting in the 1950\u201351 academic year.<ref name=viking/> He served as an assistant coach for the football team who finished with a 5\u20135 record in 1950.<ref>{{cite web| title = 2017 Presbyterian Blue Hose Football Media Guide | work =All-Time Results | publisher =Presbyterian College| date =2017 | url =https://www.nmnathletics.com/pdf9/5449812.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1951, he received a phone call from [[Ralph Jordan|Ralph \"Shug\" Jordan]], [[Auburn University]]'s newly-appointed head football coach.<ref name=viking/> Jordan had been an assistant football coach and the head basketball coach at Georgia while Lorendo was attending as a student-athlete, and wanted Lorendo to join him on Auburn's football staff.<ref name=viking/> Lorendo accepted, and he, his wife, and their newborn son relocated to [[Auburn, Alabama]].<ref name=viking/> Lorendo spent the next twenty-five seasons serving in various assistant coaching roles (1951\u20131975), and he earned a reputation as being tough yet fair.<ref name=viking/> His coaching method was described as \"old school\"<ref name=viking/> and he would punish players who he felt were not giving 100% effort in practice or games.<ref name=viking/> Lorendo was later quoted as telling his players, \"If I've been yelling and [[Profanity|cussing]] at you in past seasons, it is only because you had a chance to help the team.\"<ref name=viking/>\n\nLorendo's notable accomplishments as Auburn's assistant coach include coaching the wide receivers during the [[1957 Auburn Tigers football team|1957 national championship year]], as well as recruiting and coaching [[Pat Sullivan (American football)|Pat Sullivan]], an [[1971 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] and [[Heisman Trophy]] [[List of Heisman Trophy winners|winner]] in 1971.<ref name=support/>\n\n===Basketball===\nIn Lorendo's only year at Presbyterian, he served as the [[Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball|men's basketball team]]'s head coach.<ref name=viking/> They finished with a 17\u20139 overall record and won both the [[South Carolina Little Four]] regular season and conference tournament titles.<ref>{{cite web| title = 2008\u201309 Presbyterian Blue Hose Men's Basketball Media Guide | work =Year-by-Year Results | publisher =Presbyterian College| date =2008 | url =https://www.nmnathletics.com//pdf4/150349.pdf?_ga=2.125386957.674819792.1561052142-617336956.1561052142 |format=PDF| accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Minnesota State High School Coaches Association website also lists Lorendo as having coached Northome-Kelliher High School for one season, compiling a 6\u201316 overall record, but it does not state the specific season in which this occurred.<ref>{{cite web| title = MBCA All-Time Coaching Records | work =MHSCSA.org | publisher =Minnesota State High School Coaches Association| date =October 22, 2017| url =https://www.mshsca.org/news_article/show/847368 | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start\n | type       = coach\n | conference = \n | postseason =\n | poll       =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball|Presbyterian Blue Hose]]\n | conference = [[South Carolina Little Four]]\n | startyear  = 1950\n | endyear    = 1951\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = confboth\n | season       = 1950\u201351\n | name         = Presbyterian\n | overall      = 17\u20139\n | conference   = 5\u20131\n | confstanding = 1st\n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Presbyterian\n | overall    = 17\u20139\n | confrecord = 5\u20131\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End\n| overall = 17\u20139\n}}\n\n==Legacy==\nGene Lorendo's life was chronicled in a biography, ''Lorendo'', written by sportswriter Kenneth Ringer (2015).<ref name=book/><ref>{{cite web| title = Rome High grad publishes book about Gene Lorendo | work =[[Rome News-Tribune]] | publisher =Otis Raybon| date =December 31, 2015| url =http://www.northwestgeorgianews.com/rome-high-grad-publishes-book-about-gene-lorendo/article_4207bb61-2771-502a-a240-6ac431640bf3.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> He died on April 15, 2001 in [[Alpharetta, Georgia]].<ref name=peach/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Packers1950DraftPicks}}\n{{1957 Auburn Tigers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lorendo, Gene}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Auburn Tigers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:College men's basketball head coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs basketball players]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:High school basketball coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Oshkosh All-Stars players]]\n[[Category:People from Gilbert, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian Blue Hose football coaches]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football and basketball coach}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Gene Lorendo\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1921|12|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Gilbert, Minnesota]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2001|4|15|1921|12|7}}\n| death_place = [[Alpharetta, Georgia]]\n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1947\u20131949\n| player_team2 = [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]]\n| player_sport3 = Basketball\n| player_years4 = 1942\u20131943\n| player_team4 = [[Oshkosh All-Stars]]\n| player_years5 = 1946\u20131949\n| player_team5 = [[Georgia Bulldogs basketball|Georgia]]\n| player_positions = [[End (gridiron football)|End]] (football)<br/>[[Forward (basketball)|Forward]] (basketball)\n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1950\n| coach_team2 = [[Presbyterian Blue Hose football|Presbyterian]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1951\u20131975\n| coach_team3 = [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] (assistant)\n| coach_sport4 = Basketball\n| coach_years5 = 1950\u20131951\n| coach_team5 = [[Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball|Presbyterian]]\n| overall_record = 17\u20139 (basketball)\n| championships = \n;Basketball:\n* [[South Carolina Little Four|SCLF]] regular season (1951)\n* SCLF Tournament (1951)\n| awards = \n}}\n'''Eugene Lionel Lorendo''' (December 7, 1921 \u2013 April 15, 2001) was an American college [[American football|football]] and [[basketball]] coach, as well as a professional basketball player for one season. He played in the [[National Basketball League (United States)|National Basketball League]] for the [[Oshkosh All-Stars]] in 1942\u201343, served as [[Presbyterian College]]'s head men's basketball coach in 1950\u201351, but is perhaps most remembered for his twenty-five seasons spent as an assistant football coach for [[Auburn University]] between 1951 and 1975.\n\n==Early life and playing careers==\nA native of [[Gilbert, Minnesota]], Lorendo attended Gilbert High School and [[varsity letter|lettered]] in football, basketball, and track.<ref name=book>{{cite web| last=Blankenship |first=Allison | title = 'Lorendo' follows untold story of former AU assistant coach | work =Auburn Villager| publisher =| date =November 19, 2015 | url =https://www.auburnvillager.com/news/lorendo-follows-untold-story-of-former-au-assistant-coach/article_b29db1a6-8ecd-11e5-bce3-eb3f8042d82c.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=pfarchives>{{cite web| title = Gene Lorendo | work =| publisher =Pro Football Archives| date = | url =https://www.profootballarchives.com/playerl/lore00030.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=peach>{{cite web| title = Gene Lorendo | work =Peach Basket Society| publisher =| date = January 6, 2015 | url =http://peachbasketsociety.blogspot.com/2016/01/gene-lorendo.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> At 6'3\" and 215 pounds,<ref name=viking>{{cite web| title = Viking of the Plains| work =Auburn Magazine| publisher =[[Auburn University]]| date =November 12, 2015 | url =https://issuu.com/alumniau/docs/auburn-magazine-winter-2015/20 | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> and of [[French-Canadian]] descent,<ref name=viking/> Lorendo was a large man who was later written about resembling a [[viking]].<ref name=viking/> Utilizing this stature helped him play football, basketball, and track when he attended college.<ref name=support>{{cite web|last = Ringer| first=Ken |title = Coach Gene Lorendo Biography | work =Support Auburn| publisher =| date = June 27, 2016 | url =http://www.supportauburn.com/products/gallery-6 | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome sources claim that Lorendo played football and basketball at Evelith Junior College ({{circa|1940}}), the [[University of Northern Iowa]] ({{circa|1942}}), ''and'' the [[University of Georgia]] (1946\u20131949).<ref name=peach/><ref name=support/><ref name=justsports>{{cite web| title = Gene Lorendo Statistics| work =Just Sports Stats| publisher =| date = | url =https://www.justsportsstats.com/basketballstatsindex.php?player_id=lorenge01 | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=pbe>{{cite web| title = Gene Lorendo | work =| publisher =Pro Basketball Encyclopedia| date = | url =https://probasketballencyclopedia.com/player/gene-lorendo/| accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> The only verifiable statistics and records, however, can trace him to his time at Georgia.\n\nBefore Lorendo attended Georgia, he played one season of professional basketball for the [[Oshkosh All-Stars]] in the [[National Basketball League (United States)|National Basketball League]] during 1942\u201343.<ref name=peach/><ref name=bbr>{{cite web| title = Eugene Lorendo NBL stats| work =basketball-reference.com| publisher =Sports Reference LLC| date = | url =https://www.basketball-reference.com/nbl/players/l/loreneu01n.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> A [[forward (basketball)|forward]], he averaged  1.9 points per game.<ref name=bbr/> Lorendo then served in the [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] in [[World War II]]; stops during his service included [[Pearl Harbor]], [[Iwo Jima]], and [[Okinawa]].<ref name=support/><ref name=book/>\n\nWhen Lorendo enrolled at the University of Georgia in fall 1946, he joined the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|football]], [[Georgia Bulldogs basketball|basketball]], and [[Georgia Bulldogs track and field|track]] teams.<ref name=support/><ref>{{cite web| title = All-Time Georgia Football Lettermen | work =GeorgiaDogs.com | publisher =University of Georgia| date =February 15, 2002 | url =https://georgiadogs.com/news/2002/2/15/All_Time_Georgia_Football_Lettermen.aspx | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> In football he played [[wide receiver]], where in 1949 he led the [[Southeastern Conference]] in receiving.<ref name=support/> He also appeared in three [[bowl game]]s: the [[1947 Sugar Bowl]], [[1948 Gator Bowl]], and [[1949 Orange Bowl]].<ref name=support/>\n\nIn spring 1950, he was chosen in the [[1950 NFL Draft]] by the [[Green Bay Packers]] (11th round, 134th overall) but never played a game in the league.<ref name=pfarchives/>\n\n==Coaching careers==\n===Football===\nOnce Lorendo's playing days were over, he accepted [[Presbyterian College]]'s offer to coach football and basketball, starting in the 1950\u201351 academic year.<ref name=viking/> He served as an assistant coach for the football team who finished with a 5\u20135 record in 1950.<ref>{{cite web| title = 2017 Presbyterian Blue Hose Football Media Guide | work =All-Time Results | publisher =Presbyterian College| date =2017 | url =https://www.nmnathletics.com/pdf9/5449812.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1951, he received a phone call from [[Ralph Jordan|Ralph \"Shug\" Jordan]], [[Auburn University]]'s newly-appointed head football coach.<ref name=viking/> Jordan had been an assistant football coach and the head basketball coach at Georgia while Lorendo was attending as a student-athlete, and wanted Lorendo to join him on Auburn's football staff.<ref name=viking/> Lorendo accepted, and he, his wife, and their newborn son relocated to [[Auburn, Alabama]].<ref name=viking/> Lorendo spent the next twenty-five seasons serving in various assistant coaching roles (1951\u20131975), and he earned a reputation as being tough yet fair.<ref name=viking/> His coaching method was described as \"old school\"<ref name=viking/> and he would punish players who he felt were not giving 100% effort in practice or games.<ref name=viking/> Lorendo was later quoted as telling his players, \"If I've been yelling and [[Profanity|cussing]] at you in past seasons, it is only because you had a chance to help the team.\"<ref name=viking/>\n\nLorendo's notable accomplishments as Auburn's assistant coach include coaching the wide receivers during the [[1957 Auburn Tigers football team|1957 national championship year]], as well as recruiting and coaching [[Pat Sullivan (American football)|Pat Sullivan]], an [[1971 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] and [[Heisman Trophy]] [[List of Heisman Trophy winners|winner]] in 1971.<ref name=support/>\n\n===Basketball===\nIn Lorendo's only year at Presbyterian, he served as the [[Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball|men's basketball team]]'s head coach.<ref name=viking/> They finished with a 17\u20139 overall record and won both the [[South Carolina Little Four]] regular season and conference tournament titles.<ref>{{cite web| title = 2008\u201309 Presbyterian Blue Hose Men's Basketball Media Guide | work =Year-by-Year Results | publisher =Presbyterian College| date =2008 | url =https://www.nmnathletics.com//pdf4/150349.pdf?_ga=2.125386957.674819792.1561052142-617336956.1561052142 |format=PDF| accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Minnesota State High School Coaches Association website also lists Lorendo as having coached Northome-Kelliher High School for one season, compiling a 6\u201316 overall record, but it does not state in which specific season this occurred.<ref>{{cite web| title = MBCA All-Time Coaching Records | work =MHSCSA.org | publisher =Minnesota State High School Coaches Association| date =October 22, 2017| url =https://www.mshsca.org/news_article/show/847368 | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start\n | type       = coach\n | conference = \n | postseason =\n | poll       =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball|Presbyterian Blue Hose]]\n | conference = [[South Carolina Little Four]]\n | startyear  = 1950\n | endyear    = 1951\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = confboth\n | season       = 1950\u201351\n | name         = Presbyterian\n | overall      = 17\u20139\n | conference   = 5\u20131\n | confstanding = 1st\n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Presbyterian\n | overall    = 17\u20139\n | confrecord = 5\u20131\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End\n| overall = 17\u20139\n}}\n\n==Legacy==\nGene Lorendo's life was chronicled in a biography, ''Lorendo'', written by sportswriter Kenneth Ringer (2015).<ref name=book/><ref>{{cite web| title = Rome High grad publishes book about Gene Lorendo | work =[[Rome News-Tribune]] | publisher =Otis Raybon| date =December 31, 2015| url =http://www.northwestgeorgianews.com/rome-high-grad-publishes-book-about-gene-lorendo/article_4207bb61-2771-502a-a240-6ac431640bf3.html | accessdate = June 20, 2019}}</ref> He died on April 15, 2001 in [[Alpharetta, Georgia]].<ref name=peach/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Packers1950DraftPicks}}\n{{1957 Auburn Tigers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lorendo, Gene}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Auburn Tigers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:College men's basketball head coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs basketball players]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:High school basketball coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Oshkosh All-Stars players]]\n[[Category:People from Gilbert, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian Blue Hose football coaches]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball coaches]]\n", "name_user": "SportsGuy789", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBasketball", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene_Lorendo"}
{"title_page": "Hatch Act of 1939", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Hatch Act (disambiguation){{!}}Hatch Act}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n| name = Hatch Act of 1939\n| fullname = An Act to Prevent Pernicious Political Activities\n| acronym =\n| nickname =\n| enacted by = 76th\n| effective date = {{date|August 2, 1939|mdy}}\n| public law url =\n| cite public law = {{USPL|76|252}}\n| cite statutes at large = {{USStat|53|1147}}\n| acts amended =\n| title amended = <!--US code titles changed-->\n| sections created = <!--{{UnitedStatesCode}} can be used-->\n| sections amended =\n| leghisturl =\n| introducedin = Senate\n| introducedbill = {{USBill|76|S.|1871}}\n| introducedby = [[Carl Hatch]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[New Mexico|NM]])\n| introduceddate =\n| committees =\n| passedbody1 = Senate\n| passeddate1 =\n| passedvote1 = \n| passedbody2 = House\n| passeddate2 =\n| passedvote2 =\n| agreedbody3 =\n| agreeddate3 =\n| agreedvote3 =\n| signedpresident = [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n| signeddate = August 2, 1939\n| amendments = 1993, 2012\n}}\n\nThe '''Hatch Act of 1939''', '''An Act to Prevent Pernicious Political Activities''', is a [[United States federal law]] whose main provision prohibits [[civil servants|employees]] in the executive branch of the federal government, except the president, vice president, and certain designated high-level officials,<ref>{{cite web |first1=Cynthia |last1=Brown |first2=Jack |last2=Maskell |title=Hatch Act Restrictions on Federal Employees' Political Activities in the Digital Age |url=http://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R44469.pdf |work=[[Congressional Research Service]] |page=4 |date=April 13, 2016 |accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> from engaging in some forms of political activity. It went into law on August 2, 1939.  The law was named for [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Carl Hatch]] of New Mexico. It was most recently amended in 2012.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Hatch Act\n| encyclopedia = Encyclopedia Britannica\n| url = https://www.britannica.com/topic/Hatch-Act-United-States-1939\n| date = 20 July 1998\n| accessdate = 13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nWidespread allegations that local [[History of the Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] politicians used employees of the [[Works Progress Administration]] (WPA) during the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1938|congressional elections of 1938]] provided the immediate impetus for the passage of the Hatch Act. Criticism centered on [[swing state]]s such as Kentucky,<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://www.filsonhistorical.org/programs-and-publications/publications/the-filson-club-history-quarterly/1972-76.aspx|author= Robert J. Leupold|title= The Kentucky WPA: Relief and Politics, May\u2013November, 1935|journal= Filson Club History Quarterly|year= 1975|volume= 49|issue= 2|pages= 152\u2013168|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120328215201/http://www.filsonhistorical.org/programs-and-publications/publications/the-filson-club-history-quarterly/1972-76.aspx|archivedate= 2012-03-28}}</ref> Tennessee, Pennsylvania, and Maryland. In Pennsylvania, Republicans and dissident Democrats publicized evidence that Democratic politicians were consulted on the appointment of WPA administrators and case workers and that they used WPA jobs to gain unfair political advantage.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Priscilla F. Clement|title=The Works Progress Administration In Pennsylvania: 1935\u20131940|journal=Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography|year=1971|volume=95|issue =2|pages=244\u2013260|jstor=20090543}}</ref> In 1938, a series of newspaper articles exposed WPA patronage, and political contributions in return for employment, prompting an investigation by the Senate Campaign Expenditures Committee, headed by Sen. [[Morris Sheppard]], a Texas Democrat.<ref>{{cite book |last=Tindall |first=George B.|title=The Emergence of the New South, 1913\u20131945|year=1967|publisher=Louisiana State University Press |pages=[https://archive.org/details/emergenceofnewso00tind/page/629 629]\u201320|url=https://archive.org/details/emergenceofnewso00tind|url-access=registration |isbn=9780807100202}}</ref>\n\nDespite that investigation's inconclusive findings, many in both parties determined to take action against the growing power of the WPA and its chief administrator, [[Harry Hopkins]], an intimate of President Roosevelt. The Act was sponsored by Senator [[Carl Hatch]], a Democrat from New Mexico. At the time, Roosevelt was struggling to purge the Democratic party of its more conservative members, who were increasingly aligned with the administration's Republican opponents. The president considered vetoing the legislation or allowing it to become law without his signature, but instead signed it on the last day he could do so. His signing message welcomed the legislation as if he had called for it, and emphasized the protection his administration would provide for political expression on the part of public employees.<ref name=smith>{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Jason Scott|title=Building New Deal Liberalism: The Political Economy of Public Works, 1933\u20131956|year=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=NY|pages=184\u20136|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_PWpdRTYrGwC&pg=PA184|isbn=9780521828055}}</ref>\n\n==Provisions==\nThe 1939 Act forbids the intimidation or bribery of voters and restricts political campaign activities by federal employees. It prohibits using any public funds designated for relief or public works for electoral purposes. It forbids officials paid with federal funds from using promises of jobs, promotion, financial assistance, contracts, or any other benefit to coerce campaign contributions or political support. It provides that persons below the policy-making level in the executive branch of the federal government must not only refrain from political practices that would be illegal for any citizen, but must abstain from \"any active part\" in political campaigns, using this language to specify those who are exempt:<ref name=outside>{{cite news|title=Envoys Declared Outside Hatch Act|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/10/24/112770836.pdf|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=24 October 1940}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n*(i) an employee paid from an appropriation for the Executive Office of the President; or\n*(ii) an employee appointed by the President, by and with the advice and consent of the Senate, whose position is located within the United States, who determines policies to be pursued by the United States in the nationwide administration of Federal laws.\n\nThe act also precludes federal employees from membership in \"any political organization which advocates the overthrow of our constitutional form of government,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Moynihan|first=Daniel Patrick|title=Secrecy: The American Experience|year=1998|publisher=Yale University Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/secrecyamericane00moyn/page/159 159]|url=https://archive.org/details/secrecyamericane00moyn|url-access=registration|isbn=0300080794}}</ref> a provision meant to prohibit membership in organizations on the far left and far right, such as the [[Communist Party USA]] and the [[German-American Bund]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Stone|first=Geoffrey R.|title=Perilous Times: Free Speech in Wartime from the Sedition Act of 1798 to the War on Terrorism|year=2004|publisher=W.W. Norton|pages=[https://archive.org/details/periloustimesfre00ston/page/342 342]|url=https://archive.org/details/periloustimesfre00ston|url-access=registration|isbn=9780393058802}}</ref>\n\nAn amendment on July 19, 1940, extended the Act to certain employees of state and local governments whose positions are primarily paid for by federal funds. It has been interpreted to bar political activity on the part of employees of state agencies administering federal unemployment insurance programs and appointed local law enforcement agency officials with oversight of federal grant funds. The Hatch Act bars state and local government employees from running for public office if any federal funds support the position, even if the position is funded almost entirely with local funds.<ref>Jason C. Miller, [http://papers.ssrn.com/abstract=1444192 The Unwise and Unconstitutional Hatch Act: Why State and Local Government Employees Should be Free to Run for Public Office], 34 S. Ill. U. L.J.___ (forthcoming 2010)</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Merit Systems Protection Board|Merit Systems Protection Board]] and the [[United States Office of Special Counsel|Office of Special Counsel]] (OSC) are responsible for enforcement of the Hatch Act.<ref>William V. Luneburg. [http://www.enotes.com/hatch-act-1939-reference/hatch-act-1939 Hatch Act (1939)]. enotes.com</ref>\n\n==Supreme Court challenges==\n{{see|United Public Workers v. Mitchell|United States Civil Service Commission v. National Association of Letter Carriers}}\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] has several times declined to hear challenges to the act and has twice upheld its constitutionality. In a 1947 case brought by the CIO, a divided court found that Congress had properly exercised its authority as long as it had not affected voting rights. Justice [[William O. Douglas]] objected to the assertion that \"clean politics\" required the act's restrictions: \"it would hardly seem to be imperative to muzzle millions of citizens because some of them, if left to their constitutional freedoms, might corrupt the political process.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Walz|first=Jay|title=CIO Fails in Highest Court to Void 'Clean Politics' Act|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1947/02/11/93788947.pdf|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=February 11, 1947}}</ref> In 1973, in a case brought by the National Association of Letter Carriers, a 6 to 3 decision found the act neither too broad nor unclear. The court's three most liberal justices, Douglas, [[William J. Brennan]], and [[Thurgood Marshall]], dissented. Douglas wrote: \"It is no concern of government what an employee does in his or her spare time, whether religion, recreation, social work or politics is his hobby, unless what he or she does impairs efficiency or other facets of the merits of his job.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Supreme Court Upholds Hatch Act, 6\u20133; Says Curbs on Political Activity Are Fair |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1973/06/26/90448889.pdf |accessdate=June 12, 2013 |newspaper=New York Times|date=June 26, 1973}}</ref>\n\n==Amendments==\nIn 1975, the House passed legislation allowing federal employees to participate in partisan elections and run for office, but the Senate took no action.<ref>{{cite news|last=Madden|first=Richard|title=Congressional Session Marked by Clashes with Ford on Energy and Tax Cut|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1975/12/21/355379892.pdf|accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 21, 1975}}</ref> In 1976, Democrats who controlled Congress had sought to win support by adding protections against the coercion of employees by their superiors and federal employee unions had supported the legislation. It passed the House on a vote of 241 to 164 and the Senate on a vote of 54 to 36. President [[Gerald Ford|Ford]] vetoed the legislation on April 12. He noted that coercion could be too subtle for the law to eliminate and that the Supreme Court had said in 1973 that the Hatch Act had achieved \"a delicate balance between fair and effective government and the First Amendment rights of individual employees.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Naughton|first=James M.|title=Ford Vetoes Bill to Ease Hatch Act|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1976/04/13/92222459.pdf|accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=April 13, 1976}}</ref> President [[Jimmy Carter|Carter]] proposed similar legislation in 1977.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weaver, Jr.|first=Warren|title=Carter Proposes End of Electoral College in Presidential Votes|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1977/03/23/75054281.pdf|accessdate=13 June 2013 |newspaper=New York Times|date=March 23, 1977}}</ref> A proposed amendment to permit federal workers to participate in political campaigns passed the House on a 305 to 112 vote in 1987.<ref name=curbs>{{cite news|last=Pear|first=Robert |title=House Approves Bill to Lift Curbs On Federal Employees in Politics|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/18/us/house-approves-bill-to-lift-curbs-on-federal-employees-in-politics.html|accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times |date=November 18, 1987}}</ref> In 1990 a similar bill passed the House on a vote of 334 to 87 and the Senate on a vote of 67 to 30. President [[George H.W. Bush]] vetoed the legislation,<ref>{{cite news|last=Dowd|first=Maureen|title=President Vetoes a Bill and Makes a Threat on Second|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/16/us/president-vetoes-a-bill-and-makes-threat-on-second.html |accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 16, 1990}}</ref> which the House voted to override 327 to 93  and the Senate sustained on a vote of 65 to 35, with 55 Democrats and 10 Republicans voting to override and 35 Republicans supporting the president's veto.<ref>{{cite news|last=Berke|first=Richard L.|title=Senate Upholds Veto of Bill On U.S. Workers in Politics|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/22/us/senate-upholds-veto-of-bill-on-us-workers-in-politics.html |accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 22, 1990}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993 the advocates for removing or modifying restrictions on the political activities of federal employees succeeded in enacting the Hatch Act Reform Amendments of 1993 (107 Stat. 1001) that removed the prohibition on participation in \"political management or political campaigns.\" Federal employees are still forbidden to use their authority to affect the results of an election. They are also forbidden to run for office in a partisan election, to solicit or receive political contributions, and to engage in political activities while on duty or on federal property.<ref>ADDED CITATION SOURCE , Retrieved Nov 4, 2016 http://uscode.house.gov/statutes/pl/103/94.pdf and specific to \"affect results of an election\" citation  : http://www.ipmall.info/sites/default/files/hosted_resources/crs/R44469_2016-04-13.pdf \u2013 page 4.</ref>\n\nPresident [[Barack Obama]] signed the Hatch Act Modernization Act of 2012 on December 28, 2012. It modified penalties under the Hatch Act to allow for disciplinary actions in addition to removal for federal employees; clarified the applicability to the District of Columbia of provisions that cover state and local governments; limited the prohibition on state and local employees running for elective office to employees whose salary is paid completely by federal loans or grants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement by the Press Secretary...|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2012/12/28/statement-press-secretary-hj-res-122-hr-3477-hr-3783-hr-3870-hr-3912-hr-|work=Statements and Releases |publisher=whitehouse.gov |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Applicability to U.S. uniformed service personnel==\nThe Hatch Act does not apply to actively serving uniformed members of the [[uniformed services of the United States]], although it does apply to [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] civil servants, as well as [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] civil servants in direct support of the [[United States Coast Guard]]. Members of the [[U.S. Armed Forces]] are subject to Department of Defense Directive 1344.10 (DoDD 1344.10), ''Political Activities by Members of the Armed Forces,'' and the spirit and intent of that directive is effectively the same as that of the Hatch Act for Federal civil servants. By agreement between the Secretary of Defense and the Secretary of Homeland Security, DoDD 1344.10 also applies to uniformed personnel of the Coast Guard at all times, whether it is operating as a service in the Department of Homeland Security or as part of the Navy under the Department of Defense. As a directive, DoDD 1344.10 is considered to be in the same category as an order or regulation, and military personnel violating its provisions can be considered in violation of Article 92 (Failure to obey order or regulation) of the [[Uniform Code of Military Justice]].<ref>[http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/134410p.pdf Directive 1344.10. Political Activities by Members of the Armed Forces]. Department of Defense (2008-02-19).</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090301054940/http://www.marines.mil/units/marforpac/Pages/JAN085.aspx Cpl. R. Drew Hendricks, \"DoD policy limits political practices in the workplace\"]. Marine Forces Pacific. marines.mil (2008-01-31).</ref><ref>Christopher Garcia. [https://web.archive.org/web/20081219014308/http://www.dod.mil/dodgc/defense_ethics/resource_library/2007Deskbook/PowerPoint_Presentations/5ECC_Political_Activities_Garcia.pdf Political Activities]. Office of Under Secretary of Defense for Personnel & Readiness.</ref>\n\nMembers of the [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]] are subject to specific Health and Human Service regulations found in Title 44, Code of Federal Regulations Part 73 Subpart F.<ref>{{cite web |title=45 CFR Part 73, Subpart F \u2013 Political Activity |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/45/part-73/subpart-F |website=Legal Information Institute |publisher=Cornell Law School |accessdate=31 May 2018}}</ref> Hatch Act guidelines for [[NOAA Commissioned Officer Corps|NOAA Corps Officers]] are provided by United States Department of Commerce, Office of the General Counsel, Ethics Law and Program Division.<ref>[https://ogc.commerce.gov/collection/ethics-law-and-programs-division US Dept of Commerce, Office of the General Counsel, Ethics Law and Programs Division (ELPD)]</ref> Career members of the Senior Executive Service, administrative law judges, and National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Corps officers are all subject to Hatch Act restrictions and have additional limitations on their off-duty political activities.<ref>[https://ogc.commerce.gov/page/political-activities US Dept of Commerce, Office of the General Counsel,Political Activities]</ref>\n\n==2006\u2013present==\n<!-- When adding recent implementations/references to the Hatch Act, please use bulleted format.  Thanks. -->\n* In 2006, the [[Utah Democratic Party]] challenged the candidacy of Ogden City Police Chief [[Jon Greiner]] for State Senate. The challenge was upheld by the  U.S. OSC because the year prior the Ogden City Police Department received a federal grant to help pay for bulletproof vests. Jon Greiner appealed the decision, remained on the ballot, won the election and served one term (2006\u20132010) as Utah State Senator while the results of the appeal were unknown.<ref>{{cite news|last=Loftin|first=Josh|title=Police chief plans to stay in Senate race|url=http://deseretnews.com/dn/view/0,1249,650203448,00.html|newspaper=[[Deseret Morning News]]|date=November 1, 2006|access-date=July 8, 2012}}</ref>\n* In January 2007, the OSC announced the results of investigations into whether certain events during the election campaigns of 2004 and 2006 violated the Hatch Act.<ref>{{cite press release|title=OSC: High Level NASA Hatch Investigations Present Cautionary Tale|url=http://www.osc.gov/documents/press/2007/pr07_04.htm|website=OSC.gov|date=January 29, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205221645/http://www.osc.gov/documents/press/2007/pr07_04.htm|archive-date=February 5, 2007|access-date=June 16, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n** It found no violation when [[Kennedy Space Center]] officials allowed Senator [[John Kerry]]'s presidential campaign to use a NASA facility for a 2004 campaign event, because no government employees worked at the facility in question. It found streaming the event to NASA employees and contractors violated the Hatch Act.\n** It reviewed a 2006 speech by NASA Administrator Dr. [[Michael D. Griffin]] in which he appeared to endorse Representative [[Tom DeLay]] for re-election. It determined that he \"should have exercised better judgment\" and took no further action.\n* In June 2007, the OSC found that [[Lurita Alexis Doan]], Administrator of the [[General Services Administration]], violated the Hatch Act when she took part in a video conference with [[Karl Rove]] and other White House officials, and sent letters asking how to help [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians get elected.<ref>\"Doan's fate up to president; Hatch Act violation could prompt firing,\" ''Federal Times'', May 28, 2007</ref>\n* In November 2007, the mayor of [[Terre Haute, Indiana]] (Kevin Burke) challenged the candidacy of mayor-elect Duke Bennett under provisions of the Act. In November 2008, the [[Indiana Court of Appeals]] ruled that Bennett, who took office after a [[Vigo County, Indiana]], judge ruled that he was eligible to serve, was ineligible under the terms of the Act. The ruling was nonbinding, pending Bennett's appeal to the [[Indiana Supreme Court]].{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n* On May 6, 2008, [[FBI]] agents raided OSC offices and the home office of its director, [[Scott Bloch]]. The raids related to an investigation into allegations that Bloch's office had attempted to [[obstruction of justice|obstruct justice]] by hiring an outside company to delete computer files beyond recovery in order to prevent authorities from proving Bloch had violated the Hatch Act by retaliating against whistle-blowers in his office, an independent U.S. government agency \"charged with protecting the rights of government whistle-blowers\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Rood|first=Justin|title=FBI Raids Bush Official's Office|url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/Blotter/story?id=4797325&page=1|website=ABCNews.Go.com|date=May 6, 2008|access-date=February 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shenon|first=Philip|title=F.B.I. Raids Office of Special Counsel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/07/washington/07inquire.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 7, 2008|access-date=February 12, 2013}}</ref>\n* In 2009 two scholars urged Congress to consider tightening the Hatch Act's restrictions.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bowman |first=James S. |last2=West |first2=Jonathan P. |title=To 'Re-Hatch' Public Employees or Not? An Ethical Analysis of the Relaxation of Restrictions on Political Activities in Public Service |journal=[[Public Administration Review]] |volume=69 |issue=1 |pages=52\u201363 |year=2009 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-6210.2008.01940.x}}</ref>\n* On September 13, 2012, the OSC charged Health and Human Services Secretary [[Kathleen Sebelius]] with violating the Hatch Act by making a political speech during an official government event. Sebelius later said she had made a mistake and that the error was \"technical\" in nature.<ref>{{cite news|title=White House indicates Sebelius won't be punished over Hatch Act violation|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/09/13/white-house-indicates-sebelius-wont-be-punished-over-hatch-act-violation/|publisher=Fox News|date=September 13, 2012|access-date=September 17, 2012}}</ref>\n* On July 18, 2016, the OSC concluded that [[Housing and Urban Development Secretary]] [[Julian Castro]] violated the Hatch Act during an interview with [[Katie Couric]].  Castro admitted the violation, but denied any intent to violate the act.<ref>{{cite news|first=Gregory|last=Korte|title=Investigation: HUD Secretary Julian Castro broke law by endorsing Clinton|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/07/18/investigation-hud-secretary-julian-castro-broke-law-endorsing-clinton-hatch-act/87263314/|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=July 18, 2016|access-date=July 20, 2016}}</ref>\n* On October 30, 2016, U.S. Senate Democratic Minority Leader [[Harry Reid]] stated that FBI Director [[James Comey]] may have violated the Hatch Act by sending a letter to the Congress on October 28, 2016, which stated that the FBI would be reopening their investigation of the [[Hillary Clinton email controversy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Harry Reid says FBI Director James Comey 'may have broken' federal law|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/10/30/harry-reid-says-fbi-director-james-comey-may-have-broken-federal-law.html|website=FoxNews.com|date=October 30, 2016|access-date=June 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Letter to Congress From F.B.I. Director on Clinton Email Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/10/28/us/politics/fbi-letter.html?_r=0|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 28, 2016|access-date=October 28, 2016}}</ref> Also on October 30, [[Richard Painter]], a chief White House ethics lawyer for the [[George W. Bush administration]], published an op-ed saying that he had filed a complaint against the FBI with the OSC and with the [[Office of Government Ethics]] about the same matter.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Painter|first1=Richard W.|title=On Clinton Emails, Did the F.B.I. Director Abuse His Power?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/30/opinion/on-clinton-emails-did-the-fbi-director-abuse-his-power.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 30, 2016|access-date=June 16, 2019}}</ref>\n* In November 2016, two Bay Area federal employees who were elected to school boards were told that they would have to resign their federal positions in order to serve on the boards, as their running for a non-partisan seat that had party political involvement contravened the Hatch Act. Both Jerrold Parsons, President of the John Swett Unified School District, and Ana Galindo-Marrone, Vice Mayor of Pacifica, chose not to serve in order to retain their federal jobs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hatch Act torpedoes Bay Area officials' re-election bids|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2016/11/05/hatch-act-torpedoes-bay-area-officials-re-election-bids/|website=East Bay Times|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref>\n* In June 2017, the OSC issued a warning to [[Dan Scavino Jr.]] for an April 2017 [[Twitter|tweet]] that Scavino sent advocating for a primary challenge against U.S. Representative [[Justin Amash]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lipton|first=Eric|title=White House Official's Political Tweet Was Illegal, Agency Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/09/us/politics/dan-scavino-hatch-act-amash.html|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=June 9, 2017|access-date=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n* In October 2017, the OSC issued a warning to [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Nikki Haley]] for a June 2017 [[Twitter|tweet]] that Haley retweeted from President [[Donald Trump]] endorsing Republican Congressional candidate [[Ralph Norman]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Zachary|title=UN ambassador Nikki Haley warned over Trump retweet|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/10/03/politics/nikki-haley-hatch-act-violation/index.html|website=CNN.com|date=October 3, 2017|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* In November 2017, former [[United States Office of Government Ethics|Office of Government Ethics]] head [[Walter Shaub]] filed a complaint against White House counselor [[Kellyanne Conway]] charging that her opposition to [[Roy Moore]] opponent [[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]] during a segment on ''[[Fox and Friends]]'' violated the Hatch Act.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gerstein|first=Josh|title=Legal complaint filed over Kellyanne Conway's comments on Roy Moore race|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/22/kellyanne-conway-hatch-act-complaint-doug-jones-comment-259147|website=POLITICO.com|date=November 22, 2017|access-date=November 23, 2017}}</ref> In March 2018, the OSC announced that Conway violated the Hatch act on that occasion and one other.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lee|first=MJ|title=Office of Special Counsel: Conway violated Hatch Act|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/06/politics/kellyanne-conway-hatch-act/index.html|website=CNN.com|date=March 6, 2018|access-date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n*In September 2018, the OSC issued a warning letter to [[Stephanie Grisham]], the Press Secretary and Communications Director for the First Lady of the United States, for violating the act by including Trump's campaign slogan in a post on her government Twitter account.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bennett|first=Kate|title=Melania Trump's spokeswoman reprimanded for Hatch Act violation|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/21/politics/melania-trump-stephanie-grisham-hatch-act/index.html|website=CNN.com|date=September 21, 2018|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n*In November 2018, the OSC ruled that six [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]] officials violated the Hatch Act after in posts to their government Twitter accounts, but declined to take disciplinary action. The OSC warned the officials\u2014[[Raj Shah]], deputy press secretary; [[Jessica Ditto]], deputy director of communications; [[Madeleine Westerhout]], executive assistant to the president; [[Helen Aguirre Ferr\u00e9]], former director of media affairs; Alyssa Farah, press secretary for the vice president; and Jacob Wood, deputy communications director of the Office of Management and Budget\u2014that future infractions would be interpreted as willful violations subject to further action.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Ellie|title=6 White House officials found in violation of the Hatch Act|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/30/politics/six-white-house-officials-hatch-act/index.html|website=CNN.com|date=December 3, 2018|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n*In June 2019, the OSC sent a [https://osc.gov/Resources/Report%20to%20the%20President%20re%20Kellyanne%20Conway%20Hatch%20Act.pdf letter] to President Trump recommending that White House counselor Kellyanne Conway be removed from federal service for repeatedly violating the Hatch Act. This report follows the March 2018 OSC finding that Conway was a \"repeat offender\" for disparaging Democratic presidential candidates while in her official capacity during televised interviews and on social media.<ref name=\"BloombergHatchAct\">{{cite news|last1=Gallu|first1=Joshua|last2=Allison|first2=Bill|title=Kellyanne Conway Should Be Removed From White House Job, U.S. Agency Says|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-13/ap-newsalert-federal-agency-recommends-kellyanne-conway-be-fired-for-repeat-violation-of-law-prohibiting-political|language=en|website=Bloomberg.com|date=June 13, 2019|access-date=June 16, 2019}}</ref> President Trump, when asked at a press conference, stated he thought the provision violated her free speech rights.<ref name=\"BloombergHatchAct\" />\n\n==Current restrictions==\n(See U.S. Office of Special Counsel \"Hatch Act for Federal Employees\")\n\n===Permitted and prohibited activities for employees who may participate in partisan political activity===\n''These federal and D.C. employees '''may''':''\n*be candidates for public office in nonpartisan elections\n*register and vote as they choose\n*assist in voter registration drives\n*express opinions about candidates and issues\n*contribute money to political organizations\n*attend political fundraising functions\n*attend and be active at political rallies and meetings\n*join and be an active member of a political party or club\n*sign nominating petitions\n*campaign for or against referendum questions, constitutional amendments, municipal ordinances\n*campaign for or against candidates in partisan elections\n*make campaign speeches for candidates in partisan elections\n*distribute campaign literature in partisan elections\n*hold office in political clubs or parties\n\n''These federal and D.C. employees '''may not''':''\n\n*use official authority or influence to interfere with an election\n*solicit or discourage political activity of anyone with business before their agency\n*solicit or receive political contributions (may be done in certain limited situations by federal labor or other employee organizations)\n*be candidates for public office in partisan elections\n*engage in political activity while:\n**on duty\n**in a government office\n**wearing an official uniform\n**using a government vehicle\n*wear partisan political buttons on duty\n\n===Agencies and employees prohibited from engaging in partisan political activity===\nEmployees of the following agencies (or agency components), or in the following categories, are subject to more extensive restrictions on their political activities than employees in other departments and agencies:\n\n*[[Administrative law judge]]s (positions described at {{UnitedStatesCode|5|5372}})\n*[[Central Intelligence Agency]]\n*Contract Appeals Boards (positions described at {{UnitedStatesCode|5|5372a}})\n*[[United States Department of Justice Criminal Division|Criminal Division (Department of Justice)]]\n*[[Defense Intelligence Agency]]\n*[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]\n*[[Federal Election Commission]]\n*[[United States Merit Systems Protection Board|Merit Systems Protection Board]]\n*[[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]\n*[[National Security Agency]]\n*[[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]]\n*Office of Criminal Investigation ([[Internal Revenue Service]])\n*Office of Investigative Programs (Customs Service)\n*Office of Law Enforcement ([[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]])\n*[[United States Office of Special Counsel]]\n*[[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]]\n*[[Senior Executive Service]] \n(career positions described at {{UnitedStatesCode|5|3132}}(a)(4))\n\n===Permitted and prohibited activities for employees who may not participate in partisan political activity===\n\n''These federal employees '''may''':''\n\n*register and vote as they choose\n*assist in voter registration drives\n*express opinions about candidates and issues\n*participate in campaigns where none of the candidates represent a political party\n*contribute money to political organizations or attend political fund raising functions\n*attend political rallies and meetings\n*join political clubs or parties\n*sign nominating petitions\n*campaign for or against referendum questions, constitutional amendments, municipal ordinances\n\n''These federal employees '''may not''':''\n\n*be candidates for public office in partisan elections\n*campaign for or against a candidate or slate of candidates in partisan elections\n*make campaign speeches\n*collect contributions or sell tickets to political fund raising functions\n*distribute campaign material in partisan elections\n*organize or manage political rallies or meetings\n*hold office in political clubs or parties\n*circulate nominating petitions\n*work to register voters for one party only\n*wear political buttons at work\n\nAdditionally, one of the early consequences of the act, were disparate court rulings in union busting cases which forbade the use of voter information from initiative and recall petitions for any purposes outside the intended elections.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Office of Personnel Management]]\n* [[United States civil service]]\n* [[Smith Act]]\n* [[House Un-American Activities Committee]]\n* ''[[U.S. Public Workers v. Mitchell]]''\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Cynthia |last2=Maskell |first2=Jack |url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R44469.pdf |title=Hatch Act Restrictions on Federal Employees' Political Activities in the Digital Age |work=[[Congressional Research Service]] |date=April 13, 2016 }}\n*{{cite journal |first=Dorothy Ganfield |last=Fowler |title=Precursors of the Hatch Act |journal=Mississippi Valley Historical Review |volume=47 |issue=2 |year=1960 |pages=247\u2013262 |jstor=1891709 |doi=10.2307/1891709 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://osc.gov/Pages/HatchAct.aspx Discussion of Hatch Act on federal, state, and local government employees by the U. S. Office of Special Counsel]\n* [http://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R43630.pdf Hatch Act: Candidacy for Office by Federal Employees in the Executive Branch] [[Congressional Research Service]]\n* [http://employment.laws.com/hatch-act-text Hatch Act Text]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hatch Act Of 1939}}\n[[Category:1939 in American law]]\n[[Category:1940 in American law]]\n[[Category:Civil service in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Legal history of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States federal government administration legislation]]\n[[Category:76th United States Congress]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Hatch Act (disambiguation){{!}}Hatch Act}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n| name = Hatch Act of 1939\n| fullname = An Act to Prevent Pernicious Political Activities\n| acronym =\n| nickname =\n| enacted by = 76th\n| effective date = {{date|August 2, 1939|mdy}}\n| public law url =\n| cite public law = {{USPL|76|252}}\n| cite statutes at large = {{USStat|53|1147}}\n| acts amended =\n| title amended = <!--US code titles changed-->\n| sections created = <!--{{UnitedStatesCode}} can be used-->\n| sections amended =\n| leghisturl =\n| introducedin = Senate\n| introducedbill = {{USBill|76|S.|1871}}\n| introducedby = [[Carl Hatch]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[New Mexico|NM]])\n| introduceddate =\n| committees =\n| passedbody1 = Senate\n| passeddate1 =\n| passedvote1 = \n| passedbody2 = House\n| passeddate2 =\n| passedvote2 =\n| agreedbody3 =\n| agreeddate3 =\n| agreedvote3 =\n| signedpresident = [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n| signeddate = August 2, 1939\n| amendments = 1993, 2012\n}}\n\nThe '''Hatch Act of 1939''', Also known as the thing Donald J. Trump violated,  officially '''An Act to Prevent Pernicious Political Activities''', is a [[United States federal law]] whose main provision prohibits [[civil servants|employees]] in the executive branch of the federal government, except the president, vice president, and certain designated high-level officials,<ref>{{cite web |first1=Cynthia |last1=Brown |first2=Jack |last2=Maskell |title=Hatch Act Restrictions on Federal Employees' Political Activities in the Digital Age |url=http://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R44469.pdf |work=[[Congressional Research Service]] |page=4 |date=April 13, 2016 |accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> from engaging in some forms of political activity. It went into law on August 2, 1939.  The law was named for [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Carl Hatch]] of New Mexico. It was most recently amended in 2012.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Hatch Act\n| encyclopedia = Encyclopedia Britannica\n| url = https://www.britannica.com/topic/Hatch-Act-United-States-1939\n| date = 20 July 1998\n| accessdate = 13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nWidespread allegations that local [[History of the Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] politicians used employees of the [[Works Progress Administration]] (WPA) during the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1938|congressional elections of 1938]] provided the immediate impetus for the passage of the Hatch Act. Criticism centered on [[swing state]]s such as Kentucky,<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://www.filsonhistorical.org/programs-and-publications/publications/the-filson-club-history-quarterly/1972-76.aspx|author= Robert J. Leupold|title= The Kentucky WPA: Relief and Politics, May\u2013November, 1935|journal= Filson Club History Quarterly|year= 1975|volume= 49|issue= 2|pages= 152\u2013168|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120328215201/http://www.filsonhistorical.org/programs-and-publications/publications/the-filson-club-history-quarterly/1972-76.aspx|archivedate= 2012-03-28}}</ref> Tennessee, Pennsylvania, and Maryland. In Pennsylvania, Republicans and dissident Democrats publicized evidence that Democratic politicians were consulted on the appointment of WPA administrators and case workers and that they used WPA jobs to gain unfair political advantage.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Priscilla F. Clement|title=The Works Progress Administration In Pennsylvania: 1935\u20131940|journal=Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography|year=1971|volume=95|issue =2|pages=244\u2013260|jstor=20090543}}</ref> In 1938, a series of newspaper articles exposed WPA patronage, and political contributions in return for employment, prompting an investigation by the Senate Campaign Expenditures Committee, headed by Sen. [[Morris Sheppard]], a Texas Democrat.<ref>{{cite book |last=Tindall |first=George B.|title=The Emergence of the New South, 1913\u20131945|year=1967|publisher=Louisiana State University Press |pages=[https://archive.org/details/emergenceofnewso00tind/page/629 629]\u201320|url=https://archive.org/details/emergenceofnewso00tind|url-access=registration |isbn=9780807100202}}</ref>\n\nDespite that investigation's inconclusive findings, many in both parties determined to take action against the growing power of the WPA and its chief administrator, [[Harry Hopkins]], an intimate of President Roosevelt. The Act was sponsored by Senator [[Carl Hatch]], a Democrat from New Mexico. At the time, Roosevelt was struggling to purge the Democratic party of its more conservative members, who were increasingly aligned with the administration's Republican opponents. The president considered vetoing the legislation or allowing it to become law without his signature, but instead signed it on the last day he could do so. His signing message welcomed the legislation as if he had called for it, and emphasized the protection his administration would provide for political expression on the part of public employees.<ref name=smith>{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Jason Scott|title=Building New Deal Liberalism: The Political Economy of Public Works, 1933\u20131956|year=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=NY|pages=184\u20136|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_PWpdRTYrGwC&pg=PA184|isbn=9780521828055}}</ref>\n\n==Provisions==\nThe 1939 Act forbids the intimidation or bribery of voters and restricts political campaign activities by federal employees. It prohibits using any public funds designated for relief or public works for electoral purposes. It forbids officials paid with federal funds from using promises of jobs, promotion, financial assistance, contracts, or any other benefit to coerce campaign contributions or political support. It provides that persons below the policy-making level in the executive branch of the federal government must not only refrain from political practices that would be illegal for any citizen, but must abstain from \"any active part\" in political campaigns, using this language to specify those who are exempt:<ref name=outside>{{cite news|title=Envoys Declared Outside Hatch Act|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/10/24/112770836.pdf|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=24 October 1940}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n*(i) an employee paid from an appropriation for the Executive Office of the President; or\n*(ii) an employee appointed by the President, by and with the advice and consent of the Senate, whose position is located within the United States, who determines policies to be pursued by the United States in the nationwide administration of Federal laws.\n\nThe act also precludes federal employees from membership in \"any political organization which advocates the overthrow of our constitutional form of government,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Moynihan|first=Daniel Patrick|title=Secrecy: The American Experience|year=1998|publisher=Yale University Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/secrecyamericane00moyn/page/159 159]|url=https://archive.org/details/secrecyamericane00moyn|url-access=registration|isbn=0300080794}}</ref> a provision meant to prohibit membership in organizations on the far left and far right, such as the [[Communist Party USA]] and the [[German-American Bund]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Stone|first=Geoffrey R.|title=Perilous Times: Free Speech in Wartime from the Sedition Act of 1798 to the War on Terrorism|year=2004|publisher=W.W. Norton|pages=[https://archive.org/details/periloustimesfre00ston/page/342 342]|url=https://archive.org/details/periloustimesfre00ston|url-access=registration|isbn=9780393058802}}</ref>\n\nAn amendment on July 19, 1940, extended the Act to certain employees of state and local governments whose positions are primarily paid for by federal funds. It has been interpreted to bar political activity on the part of employees of state agencies administering federal unemployment insurance programs and appointed local law enforcement agency officials with oversight of federal grant funds. The Hatch Act bars state and local government employees from running for public office if any federal funds support the position, even if the position is funded almost entirely with local funds.<ref>Jason C. Miller, [http://papers.ssrn.com/abstract=1444192 The Unwise and Unconstitutional Hatch Act: Why State and Local Government Employees Should be Free to Run for Public Office], 34 S. Ill. U. L.J.___ (forthcoming 2010)</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Merit Systems Protection Board|Merit Systems Protection Board]] and the [[United States Office of Special Counsel|Office of Special Counsel]] (OSC) are responsible for enforcement of the Hatch Act.<ref>William V. Luneburg. [http://www.enotes.com/hatch-act-1939-reference/hatch-act-1939 Hatch Act (1939)]. enotes.com</ref>\n\n==Supreme Court challenges==\n{{see|United Public Workers v. Mitchell|United States Civil Service Commission v. National Association of Letter Carriers}}\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] has several times declined to hear challenges to the act and has twice upheld its constitutionality. In a 1947 case brought by the CIO, a divided court found that Congress had properly exercised its authority as long as it had not affected voting rights. Justice [[William O. Douglas]] objected to the assertion that \"clean politics\" required the act's restrictions: \"it would hardly seem to be imperative to muzzle millions of citizens because some of them, if left to their constitutional freedoms, might corrupt the political process.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Walz|first=Jay|title=CIO Fails in Highest Court to Void 'Clean Politics' Act|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1947/02/11/93788947.pdf|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=February 11, 1947}}</ref> In 1973, in a case brought by the National Association of Letter Carriers, a 6 to 3 decision found the act neither too broad nor unclear. The court's three most liberal justices, Douglas, [[William J. Brennan]], and [[Thurgood Marshall]], dissented. Douglas wrote: \"It is no concern of government what an employee does in his or her spare time, whether religion, recreation, social work or politics is his hobby, unless what he or she does impairs efficiency or other facets of the merits of his job.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Supreme Court Upholds Hatch Act, 6\u20133; Says Curbs on Political Activity Are Fair |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1973/06/26/90448889.pdf |accessdate=June 12, 2013 |newspaper=New York Times|date=June 26, 1973}}</ref>\n\n==Amendments==\nIn 1975, the House passed legislation allowing federal employees to participate in partisan elections and run for office, but the Senate took no action.<ref>{{cite news|last=Madden|first=Richard|title=Congressional Session Marked by Clashes with Ford on Energy and Tax Cut|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1975/12/21/355379892.pdf|accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 21, 1975}}</ref> In 1976, Democrats who controlled Congress had sought to win support by adding protections against the coercion of employees by their superiors and federal employee unions had supported the legislation. It passed the House on a vote of 241 to 164 and the Senate on a vote of 54 to 36. President [[Gerald Ford|Ford]] vetoed the legislation on April 12. He noted that coercion could be too subtle for the law to eliminate and that the Supreme Court had said in 1973 that the Hatch Act had achieved \"a delicate balance between fair and effective government and the First Amendment rights of individual employees.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Naughton|first=James M.|title=Ford Vetoes Bill to Ease Hatch Act|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1976/04/13/92222459.pdf|accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=April 13, 1976}}</ref> President [[Jimmy Carter|Carter]] proposed similar legislation in 1977.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weaver, Jr.|first=Warren|title=Carter Proposes End of Electoral College in Presidential Votes|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1977/03/23/75054281.pdf|accessdate=13 June 2013 |newspaper=New York Times|date=March 23, 1977}}</ref> A proposed amendment to permit federal workers to participate in political campaigns passed the House on a 305 to 112 vote in 1987.<ref name=curbs>{{cite news|last=Pear|first=Robert |title=House Approves Bill to Lift Curbs On Federal Employees in Politics|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/18/us/house-approves-bill-to-lift-curbs-on-federal-employees-in-politics.html|accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times |date=November 18, 1987}}</ref> In 1990 a similar bill passed the House on a vote of 334 to 87 and the Senate on a vote of 67 to 30. President [[George H.W. Bush]] vetoed the legislation,<ref>{{cite news|last=Dowd|first=Maureen|title=President Vetoes a Bill and Makes a Threat on Second|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/16/us/president-vetoes-a-bill-and-makes-threat-on-second.html |accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 16, 1990}}</ref> which the House voted to override 327 to 93  and the Senate sustained on a vote of 65 to 35, with 55 Democrats and 10 Republicans voting to override and 35 Republicans supporting the president's veto.<ref>{{cite news|last=Berke|first=Richard L.|title=Senate Upholds Veto of Bill On U.S. Workers in Politics|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/22/us/senate-upholds-veto-of-bill-on-us-workers-in-politics.html |accessdate=June 13, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 22, 1990}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993 the advocates for removing or modifying restrictions on the political activities of federal employees succeeded in enacting the Hatch Act Reform Amendments of 1993 (107 Stat. 1001) that removed the prohibition on participation in \"political management or political campaigns.\" Federal employees are still forbidden to use their authority to affect the results of an election. They are also forbidden to run for office in a partisan election, to solicit or receive political contributions, and to engage in political activities while on duty or on federal property.<ref>ADDED CITATION SOURCE , Retrieved Nov 4, 2016 http://uscode.house.gov/statutes/pl/103/94.pdf and specific to \"affect results of an election\" citation  : http://www.ipmall.info/sites/default/files/hosted_resources/crs/R44469_2016-04-13.pdf \u2013 page 4.</ref>\n\nPresident [[Barack Obama]] signed the Hatch Act Modernization Act of 2012 on December 28, 2012. It modified penalties under the Hatch Act to allow for disciplinary actions in addition to removal for federal employees; clarified the applicability to the District of Columbia of provisions that cover state and local governments; limited the prohibition on state and local employees running for elective office to employees whose salary is paid completely by federal loans or grants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement by the Press Secretary...|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2012/12/28/statement-press-secretary-hj-res-122-hr-3477-hr-3783-hr-3870-hr-3912-hr-|work=Statements and Releases |publisher=whitehouse.gov |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Applicability to U.S. uniformed service personnel==\nThe Hatch Act does not apply to actively serving uniformed members of the [[uniformed services of the United States]], although it does apply to [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] civil servants, as well as [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] civil servants in direct support of the [[United States Coast Guard]]. Members of the [[U.S. Armed Forces]] are subject to Department of Defense Directive 1344.10 (DoDD 1344.10), ''Political Activities by Members of the Armed Forces,'' and the spirit and intent of that directive is effectively the same as that of the Hatch Act for Federal civil servants. By agreement between the Secretary of Defense and the Secretary of Homeland Security, DoDD 1344.10 also applies to uniformed personnel of the Coast Guard at all times, whether it is operating as a service in the Department of Homeland Security or as part of the Navy under the Department of Defense. As a directive, DoDD 1344.10 is considered to be in the same category as an order or regulation, and military personnel violating its provisions can be considered in violation of Article 92 (Failure to obey order or regulation) of the [[Uniform Code of Military Justice]].<ref>[http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/134410p.pdf Directive 1344.10. Political Activities by Members of the Armed Forces]. Department of Defense (2008-02-19).</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090301054940/http://www.marines.mil/units/marforpac/Pages/JAN085.aspx Cpl. R. Drew Hendricks, \"DoD policy limits political practices in the workplace\"]. Marine Forces Pacific. marines.mil (2008-01-31).</ref><ref>Christopher Garcia. [https://web.archive.org/web/20081219014308/http://www.dod.mil/dodgc/defense_ethics/resource_library/2007Deskbook/PowerPoint_Presentations/5ECC_Political_Activities_Garcia.pdf Political Activities]. Office of Under Secretary of Defense for Personnel & Readiness.</ref>\n\nMembers of the [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]] are subject to specific Health and Human Service regulations found in Title 44, Code of Federal Regulations Part 73 Subpart F.<ref>{{cite web |title=45 CFR Part 73, Subpart F \u2013 Political Activity |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/45/part-73/subpart-F |website=Legal Information Institute |publisher=Cornell Law School |accessdate=31 May 2018}}</ref> Hatch Act guidelines for [[NOAA Commissioned Officer Corps|NOAA Corps Officers]] are provided by United States Department of Commerce, Office of the General Counsel, Ethics Law and Program Division.<ref>[https://ogc.commerce.gov/collection/ethics-law-and-programs-division US Dept of Commerce, Office of the General Counsel, Ethics Law and Programs Division (ELPD)]</ref> Career members of the Senior Executive Service, administrative law judges, and National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Corps officers are all subject to Hatch Act restrictions and have additional limitations on their off-duty political activities.<ref>[https://ogc.commerce.gov/page/political-activities US Dept of Commerce, Office of the General Counsel,Political Activities]</ref>\n\n==2006\u2013present==\n<!-- When adding recent implementations/references to the Hatch Act, please use bulleted format.  Thanks. -->\n* In 2006, the [[Utah Democratic Party]] challenged the candidacy of Ogden City Police Chief [[Jon Greiner]] for State Senate. The challenge was upheld by the  U.S. OSC because the year prior the Ogden City Police Department received a federal grant to help pay for bulletproof vests. Jon Greiner appealed the decision, remained on the ballot, won the election and served one term (2006\u20132010) as Utah State Senator while the results of the appeal were unknown.<ref>{{cite news|last=Loftin|first=Josh|title=Police chief plans to stay in Senate race|url=http://deseretnews.com/dn/view/0,1249,650203448,00.html|newspaper=[[Deseret Morning News]]|date=November 1, 2006|access-date=July 8, 2012}}</ref>\n* In January 2007, the OSC announced the results of investigations into whether certain events during the election campaigns of 2004 and 2006 violated the Hatch Act.<ref>{{cite press release|title=OSC: High Level NASA Hatch Investigations Present Cautionary Tale|url=http://www.osc.gov/documents/press/2007/pr07_04.htm|website=OSC.gov|date=January 29, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205221645/http://www.osc.gov/documents/press/2007/pr07_04.htm|archive-date=February 5, 2007|access-date=June 16, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n** It found no violation when [[Kennedy Space Center]] officials allowed Senator [[John Kerry]]'s presidential campaign to use a NASA facility for a 2004 campaign event, because no government employees worked at the facility in question. It found streaming the event to NASA employees and contractors violated the Hatch Act.\n** It reviewed a 2006 speech by NASA Administrator Dr. [[Michael D. Griffin]] in which he appeared to endorse Representative [[Tom DeLay]] for re-election. It determined that he \"should have exercised better judgment\" and took no further action.\n* In June 2007, the OSC found that [[Lurita Alexis Doan]], Administrator of the [[General Services Administration]], violated the Hatch Act when she took part in a video conference with [[Karl Rove]] and other White House officials, and sent letters asking how to help [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians get elected.<ref>\"Doan's fate up to president; Hatch Act violation could prompt firing,\" ''Federal Times'', May 28, 2007</ref>\n* In November 2007, the mayor of [[Terre Haute, Indiana]] (Kevin Burke) challenged the candidacy of mayor-elect Duke Bennett under provisions of the Act. In November 2008, the [[Indiana Court of Appeals]] ruled that Bennett, who took office after a [[Vigo County, Indiana]], judge ruled that he was eligible to serve, was ineligible under the terms of the Act. The ruling was nonbinding, pending Bennett's appeal to the [[Indiana Supreme Court]].{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n* On May 6, 2008, [[FBI]] agents raided OSC offices and the home office of its director, [[Scott Bloch]]. The raids related to an investigation into allegations that Bloch's office had attempted to [[obstruction of justice|obstruct justice]] by hiring an outside company to delete computer files beyond recovery in order to prevent authorities from proving Bloch had violated the Hatch Act by retaliating against whistle-blowers in his office, an independent U.S. government agency \"charged with protecting the rights of government whistle-blowers\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Rood|first=Justin|title=FBI Raids Bush Official's Office|url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/Blotter/story?id=4797325&page=1|website=ABCNews.Go.com|date=May 6, 2008|access-date=February 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shenon|first=Philip|title=F.B.I. Raids Office of Special Counsel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/07/washington/07inquire.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 7, 2008|access-date=February 12, 2013}}</ref>\n* In 2009 two scholars urged Congress to consider tightening the Hatch Act's restrictions.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bowman |first=James S. |last2=West |first2=Jonathan P. |title=To 'Re-Hatch' Public Employees or Not? An Ethical Analysis of the Relaxation of Restrictions on Political Activities in Public Service |journal=[[Public Administration Review]] |volume=69 |issue=1 |pages=52\u201363 |year=2009 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-6210.2008.01940.x}}</ref>\n* On September 13, 2012, the OSC charged Health and Human Services Secretary [[Kathleen Sebelius]] with violating the Hatch Act by making a political speech during an official government event. Sebelius later said she had made a mistake and that the error was \"technical\" in nature.<ref>{{cite news|title=White House indicates Sebelius won't be punished over Hatch Act violation|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/09/13/white-house-indicates-sebelius-wont-be-punished-over-hatch-act-violation/|publisher=Fox News|date=September 13, 2012|access-date=September 17, 2012}}</ref>\n* On July 18, 2016, the OSC concluded that [[Housing and Urban Development Secretary]] [[Julian Castro]] violated the Hatch Act during an interview with [[Katie Couric]].  Castro admitted the violation, but denied any intent to violate the act.<ref>{{cite news|first=Gregory|last=Korte|title=Investigation: HUD Secretary Julian Castro broke law by endorsing Clinton|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/07/18/investigation-hud-secretary-julian-castro-broke-law-endorsing-clinton-hatch-act/87263314/|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=July 18, 2016|access-date=July 20, 2016}}</ref>\n* On October 30, 2016, U.S. Senate Democratic Minority Leader [[Harry Reid]] stated that FBI Director [[James Comey]] may have violated the Hatch Act by sending a letter to the Congress on October 28, 2016, which stated that the FBI would be reopening their investigation of the [[Hillary Clinton email controversy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Harry Reid says FBI Director James Comey 'may have broken' federal law|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/10/30/harry-reid-says-fbi-director-james-comey-may-have-broken-federal-law.html|website=FoxNews.com|date=October 30, 2016|access-date=June 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Letter to Congress From F.B.I. Director on Clinton Email Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/10/28/us/politics/fbi-letter.html?_r=0|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 28, 2016|access-date=October 28, 2016}}</ref> Also on October 30, [[Richard Painter]], a chief White House ethics lawyer for the [[George W. Bush administration]], published an op-ed saying that he had filed a complaint against the FBI with the OSC and with the [[Office of Government Ethics]] about the same matter.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Painter|first1=Richard W.|title=On Clinton Emails, Did the F.B.I. Director Abuse His Power?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/30/opinion/on-clinton-emails-did-the-fbi-director-abuse-his-power.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 30, 2016|access-date=June 16, 2019}}</ref>\n* In November 2016, two Bay Area federal employees who were elected to school boards were told that they would have to resign their federal positions in order to serve on the boards, as their running for a non-partisan seat that had party political involvement contravened the Hatch Act. Both Jerrold Parsons, President of the John Swett Unified School District, and Ana Galindo-Marrone, Vice Mayor of Pacifica, chose not to serve in order to retain their federal jobs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hatch Act torpedoes Bay Area officials' re-election bids|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2016/11/05/hatch-act-torpedoes-bay-area-officials-re-election-bids/|website=East Bay Times|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref>\n* In June 2017, the OSC issued a warning to [[Dan Scavino Jr.]] for an April 2017 [[Twitter|tweet]] that Scavino sent advocating for a primary challenge against U.S. Representative [[Justin Amash]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lipton|first=Eric|title=White House Official's Political Tweet Was Illegal, Agency Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/09/us/politics/dan-scavino-hatch-act-amash.html|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=June 9, 2017|access-date=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n* In October 2017, the OSC issued a warning to [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Nikki Haley]] for a June 2017 [[Twitter|tweet]] that Haley retweeted from President [[Donald Trump]] endorsing Republican Congressional candidate [[Ralph Norman]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Zachary|title=UN ambassador Nikki Haley warned over Trump retweet|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/10/03/politics/nikki-haley-hatch-act-violation/index.html|website=CNN.com|date=October 3, 2017|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* In November 2017, former [[United States Office of Government Ethics|Office of Government Ethics]] head [[Walter Shaub]] filed a complaint against White House counselor [[Kellyanne Conway]] charging that her opposition to [[Roy Moore]] opponent [[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]] during a segment on ''[[Fox and Friends]]'' violated the Hatch Act.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gerstein|first=Josh|title=Legal complaint filed over Kellyanne Conway's comments on Roy Moore race|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/22/kellyanne-conway-hatch-act-complaint-doug-jones-comment-259147|website=POLITICO.com|date=November 22, 2017|access-date=November 23, 2017}}</ref> In March 2018, the OSC announced that Conway violated the Hatch act on that occasion and one other.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lee|first=MJ|title=Office of Special Counsel: Conway violated Hatch Act|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/06/politics/kellyanne-conway-hatch-act/index.html|website=CNN.com|date=March 6, 2018|access-date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n*In September 2018, the OSC issued a warning letter to [[Stephanie Grisham]], the Press Secretary and Communications Director for the First Lady of the United States, for violating the act by including Trump's campaign slogan in a post on her government Twitter account.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bennett|first=Kate|title=Melania Trump's spokeswoman reprimanded for Hatch Act violation|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/21/politics/melania-trump-stephanie-grisham-hatch-act/index.html|website=CNN.com|date=September 21, 2018|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n*In November 2018, the OSC ruled that six [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]] officials violated the Hatch Act after in posts to their government Twitter accounts, but declined to take disciplinary action. The OSC warned the officials\u2014[[Raj Shah]], deputy press secretary; [[Jessica Ditto]], deputy director of communications; [[Madeleine Westerhout]], executive assistant to the president; [[Helen Aguirre Ferr\u00e9]], former director of media affairs; Alyssa Farah, press secretary for the vice president; and Jacob Wood, deputy communications director of the Office of Management and Budget\u2014that future infractions would be interpreted as willful violations subject to further action.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Ellie|title=6 White House officials found in violation of the Hatch Act|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/30/politics/six-white-house-officials-hatch-act/index.html|website=CNN.com|date=December 3, 2018|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n*In June 2019, the OSC sent a [https://osc.gov/Resources/Report%20to%20the%20President%20re%20Kellyanne%20Conway%20Hatch%20Act.pdf letter] to President Trump recommending that White House counselor Kellyanne Conway be removed from federal service for repeatedly violating the Hatch Act. This report follows the March 2018 OSC finding that Conway was a \"repeat offender\" for disparaging Democratic presidential candidates while in her official capacity during televised interviews and on social media.<ref name=\"BloombergHatchAct\">{{cite news|last1=Gallu|first1=Joshua|last2=Allison|first2=Bill|title=Kellyanne Conway Should Be Removed From White House Job, U.S. Agency Says|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-13/ap-newsalert-federal-agency-recommends-kellyanne-conway-be-fired-for-repeat-violation-of-law-prohibiting-political|language=en|website=Bloomberg.com|date=June 13, 2019|access-date=June 16, 2019}}</ref> President Trump, when asked at a press conference, stated he thought the provision violated her free speech rights.<ref name=\"BloombergHatchAct\" />\n\n==Current restrictions==\n(See U.S. Office of Special Counsel \"Hatch Act for Federal Employees\")\n\n===Permitted and prohibited activities for employees who may participate in partisan political activity===\n''These federal and D.C. employees '''may''':''\n*be candidates for public office in nonpartisan elections\n*register and vote as they choose\n*assist in voter registration drives\n*express opinions about candidates and issues\n*contribute money to political organizations\n*attend political fundraising functions\n*attend and be active at political rallies and meetings\n*join and be an active member of a political party or club\n*sign nominating petitions\n*campaign for or against referendum questions, constitutional amendments, municipal ordinances\n*campaign for or against candidates in partisan elections\n*make campaign speeches for candidates in partisan elections\n*distribute campaign literature in partisan elections\n*hold office in political clubs or parties\n\n''These federal and D.C. employees '''may not''':''\n\n*use official authority or influence to interfere with an election\n*solicit or discourage political activity of anyone with business before their agency\n*solicit or receive political contributions (may be done in certain limited situations by federal labor or other employee organizations)\n*be candidates for public office in partisan elections\n*engage in political activity while:\n**on duty\n**in a government office\n**wearing an official uniform\n**using a government vehicle\n*wear partisan political buttons on duty\n\n===Agencies and employees prohibited from engaging in partisan political activity===\nEmployees of the following agencies (or agency components), or in the following categories, are subject to more extensive restrictions on their political activities than employees in other departments and agencies:\n\n*[[Administrative law judge]]s (positions described at {{UnitedStatesCode|5|5372}})\n*[[Central Intelligence Agency]]\n*Contract Appeals Boards (positions described at {{UnitedStatesCode|5|5372a}})\n*[[United States Department of Justice Criminal Division|Criminal Division (Department of Justice)]]\n*[[Defense Intelligence Agency]]\n*[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]\n*[[Federal Election Commission]]\n*[[United States Merit Systems Protection Board|Merit Systems Protection Board]]\n*[[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]\n*[[National Security Agency]]\n*[[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]]\n*Office of Criminal Investigation ([[Internal Revenue Service]])\n*Office of Investigative Programs (Customs Service)\n*Office of Law Enforcement ([[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]])\n*[[United States Office of Special Counsel]]\n*[[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]]\n*[[Senior Executive Service]] \n(career positions described at {{UnitedStatesCode|5|3132}}(a)(4))\n\n===Permitted and prohibited activities for employees who may not participate in partisan political activity===\n\n''These federal employees '''may''':''\n\n*register and vote as they choose\n*assist in voter registration drives\n*express opinions about candidates and issues\n*participate in campaigns where none of the candidates represent a political party\n*contribute money to political organizations or attend political fund raising functions\n*attend political rallies and meetings\n*join political clubs or parties\n*sign nominating petitions\n*campaign for or against referendum questions, constitutional amendments, municipal ordinances\n\n''These federal employees '''may not''':''\n\n*be candidates for public office in partisan elections\n*campaign for or against a candidate or slate of candidates in partisan elections\n*make campaign speeches\n*collect contributions or sell tickets to political fund raising functions\n*distribute campaign material in partisan elections\n*organize or manage political rallies or meetings\n*hold office in political clubs or parties\n*circulate nominating petitions\n*work to register voters for one party only\n*wear political buttons at work\n\nAdditionally, one of the early consequences of the act, were disparate court rulings in union busting cases which forbade the use of voter information from initiative and recall petitions for any purposes outside the intended elections.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Office of Personnel Management]]\n* [[United States civil service]]\n* [[Smith Act]]\n* [[House Un-American Activities Committee]]\n* ''[[U.S. Public Workers v. Mitchell]]''\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Cynthia |last2=Maskell |first2=Jack |url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R44469.pdf |title=Hatch Act Restrictions on Federal Employees' Political Activities in the Digital Age |work=[[Congressional Research Service]] |date=April 13, 2016 }}\n*{{cite journal |first=Dorothy Ganfield |last=Fowler |title=Precursors of the Hatch Act |journal=Mississippi Valley Historical Review |volume=47 |issue=2 |year=1960 |pages=247\u2013262 |jstor=1891709 |doi=10.2307/1891709 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://osc.gov/Pages/HatchAct.aspx Discussion of Hatch Act on federal, state, and local government employees by the U. S. Office of Special Counsel]\n* [http://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R43630.pdf Hatch Act: Candidacy for Office by Federal Employees in the Executive Branch] [[Congressional Research Service]]\n* [http://employment.laws.com/hatch-act-text Hatch Act Text]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hatch Act Of 1939}}\n[[Category:1939 in American law]]\n[[Category:1940 in American law]]\n[[Category:Civil service in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Legal history of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States federal government administration legislation]]\n[[Category:76th United States Congress]]\n", "name_user": "Tmanx11", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hatch_Act_of_1939"}
